// cmux-watchdog — the cmux capture/classification layer + a deterministic
// tiered remediator for failed cmux panes. It is the SOLE place that reads and
// classifies cmux: a one-shot `snapshot` produces a versioned capture envelope
// (every surface's type + state + redacted scrollback) that downstream skills
// like cmux-observability rebuild their view from with zero cmux calls. The
// remediation side is decoupled into an always-on capture/detection producer
// and an optional consumer agent. watchdog.py owns the mechanical loop (scan /
// watch), the journaling, the digest cursor, and the two safe fixes (send-enter,
// resend). A single detached `watch` process appends findings to an inbox file
// and journals pane output regardless of whether any agent is attached. When a
// consumer agent runs this skill it drains the backlog, then tails the inbox:
// it auto-fixes safe findings, hands risky ones to a designated handler agent
// via the p2p skill without blocking, and summarizes journals into Obsidian
// worklog bullets. The binary never calls a model and never shells out to p2p
// or tfork — the agent does that through those skills.

skill cmux_watchdog(scope = none <"Which panes to watch: omit for the caller's own workspace, pass a workspace title or ref (workspace:N / UUID) for one workspace, or the literal `all` for every workspace.">, interval = 6 <"Seconds between scans in the continuous watch loop. Ignored when {once} is set.">, once = false <"Run a single scan-and-remediate pass instead of the continuous watch loop. Use for a one-off check. No producer, inbox, journaling, or worklog summaries happen in this mode.">, report_only = false <"List every detected failure and its suggested fix but take no action at all — not even the safe send-enter or a handler hand-off. Overrides tiered auto-remediation.">, summary_interval = 3600 <"Seconds between automatic worklog-summary passes. The detached producer emits a summarize_due event each interval; on each one (and once on attach) the consumer runs the agent-authored summary pass (summarize.py collect -> its own subagents author bullets -> record-summaries), unless a durable launchd job owns summarization, in which case the consumer defers and the tick is a no-op. The same value is the default --interval for that launchd summarizer (summarize.py install), which uses the HTTP backend. Set 0 to disable the producer's ticks (pure capture + detection); the launchd job, if installed, still summarizes on its own clock. Ignored when {once} is set.">, handler = none <"The cmux tab title of the standing handler agent that risky findings are handed off to via the p2p skill. When omitted, risky findings are surfaced to the user instead, since there is no handler to route to.">)
    description: "The cmux capture/classification layer + remediator. `watchdog.py snapshot` is the one-shot, read-only, SOLE reader of cmux: it emits a versioned capture envelope (workspaces + surfaces incl. browsers, per-agent type/state, redacted scrollback) that view-layer skills like cmux-observability rebuild from with zero cmux calls. Beyond capture it watches panes via an always-on detached producer that captures, detects, and journals; when a consumer agent is attached it auto-fixes safe findings (send-enter, learned resends) and hands risky ones to the handler agent via the p2p skill without blocking. Summarization is owned by a separate sibling, summarize.py, which turns journaled output into Obsidian worklog bullets — by default the attached consumer's own subagents author them (no API key; collect -> record-summaries), or with no agent attached a durable launchd job calls an OpenAI-compatible LLM (DeepSeek-V4 default). Exactly one owner at a time; it catches up any unsummarized backlog."

    context:
        binary_contract
        summarizer_component
        failure_signatures
        journal_model
        inbox_model

    constraints:
        must boundary_returns_handoffs
        must auto_safe_handoff_risky
        must single_summary_owner
        require local_only
        avoid focus_changes

    flow:
        "Resolve <skill-dir> to the absolute directory this SKILL.md was loaded from — watchdog.py sits in that same directory, and the working directory is the user's project, not the skill directory, so a bare watchdog.py will not resolve. Every subcommand below runs as: python3 <skill-dir>/watchdog.py <subcommand>."

        if once
            "Run: python3 <skill-dir>/watchdog.py scan, appending --workspace {scope} when {scope} is set. Parse stdout as one JSON object; its candidates array is the findings to process below. A one-shot scan starts no producer, writes no inbox, journals nothing, and runs no summaries — it is a pure point-in-time check."
        else
            ensure_producer_running(scope, interval, summary_interval)
            "Do NOT install or load the launchd summarizer during normal attached-consumer runs. The default attached path is agent-authored summaries (summarize.py collect -> subagents -> record-summaries), so no LLM API key or durable HTTP job is needed. Only if the user explicitly asks to set up durable/no-agent summarization: if ~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.cmux-watchdog.summarizer.plist is absent, run python3 <skill-dir>/summarize.py install --interval {summary_interval} --workspace {scope} (or 'all' when {scope} is unset) --load, and make sure LLM_API_KEY (or DEEPSEEK_API_KEY) and OBSIDIAN live in ~/.cmux-watchdog/summarizer.env or ~/genesis/.env — launchd does not inherit your shell env. This is what makes hourly summaries happen overnight without a consumer; see summarizer_component and single_summary_owner."
            "On attach, run python3 <skill-dir>/watchdog.py scan once (appending --workspace {scope} when {scope} is set) to catch failures that became active while no consumer was attached — the producer re-emits a finding only after it clears and recurs, so a one-shot scan is the catch-up. Its candidates, together with every NDJSON line later tailed from the inbox, are the events processed below."
            run_worklog_summary(scope)
            "Tail the inbox file ~/.cmux-watchdog/inbox/findings.ndjson with the Monitor tool: each newly appended NDJSON line is one event — a watching banner, a finding, or a summarize_due tick. Dispatch each by type and keep looping until the user asks to stop; the skill owns this loop. Do not launch your own watch — the detached producer is the single writer, and a second watcher would double-journal."

        if "the event is a summarize_due tick, or the user has explicitly asked for an ad-hoc worklog summary pass"
            run_worklog_summary(scope)
        else
            "Otherwise this event is a failure finding — a scan candidate (once mode or the attach catch-up) or a finding line tailed from the inbox. Process it by its tier, using its surface_ref, workspace_ref, signature, label, and redacted evidence."
            process_failure_finding(report_only, handler)

block ensure_producer_running(scope, interval, summary_interval)
    description: "Make sure the single always-on detached producer is capturing, detecting, and journaling, launching it if absent."

    flow:
        "Check whether a detached producer is already running — a `watchdog.py watch` process whose stdout is appended to the inbox file ~/.cmux-watchdog/inbox/findings.ndjson (e.g. via `pgrep -f 'watchdog.py watch'`). If one is already running, do not start another: there must be exactly one producer, because the re-emit-after-clear dedup state lives in that single process and a second would double-journal the same panes."
        "If none is running, create ~/.cmux-watchdog/inbox/ if needed and launch the producer detached so it outlives this agent: nohup python3 <skill-dir>/watchdog.py watch --interval {interval} --summary-interval {summary_interval} (appending --workspace {scope} when {scope} is set), redirecting stdout appended to ~/.cmux-watchdog/inbox/findings.ndjson, run in the background and disowned. It then captures, detects, and journals every tick, appending findings and summarize_due ticks to the inbox whether or not any consumer is attached."

block run_worklog_summary(scope)
    description: "Summarize newly-captured pane output into the Obsidian daily worklog. Single-owner aware: defers to the durable launchd job when it is the active owner; otherwise the attached consumer runs the pass itself, authoring the bullets with its own subagents (no LLM API key) via summarize.py collect -> record-summaries."

    flow:
        if "the durable launchd summarizer is the active owner (launchctl print gui/<uid>/com.cmux-watchdog.summarizer exits 0) and this is an explicit user 'summarize now' request"
            "Kickstart the active launchd owner instead of digesting yourself: run launchctl kickstart gui/<uid>/com.cmux-watchdog.summarizer (or the configured label from summarize.py install's status_cmd/load_cmd), then report that the durable summarizer owns the immediate pass. Do NOT run summarize.py collect / digest while launchd is loaded."
        elif "the durable launchd summarizer is the active owner (launchctl print gui/<uid>/com.cmux-watchdog.summarizer exits 0)"
            "Defer — do NOT run summarize.py collect / digest here: it would race launchd's shared per-surface cursor and split the hour's lines (single_summary_owner). On an automatic summarize_due tick this makes the tick a no-op and on attach it skips the drain; the launchd job summarizes on its own clock and its catch-up covers any backlog within the 1-day cap."
        else
            "Run the agent-authored summary pass — the default when no launchd job owns summarization. Your own subagents write the bullets, so it needs no LLM API key, only $OBSIDIAN. Three steps: (1) Run python3 <skill-dir>/summarize.py collect, appending --workspace {scope} when {scope} is set. Under an advisory lock it shells out to watchdog.py digest (advancing each surface's read-cursor) and registers the new digests in the durable summary_state.json manifest, then prints {ok, pending: [{digest_file, date, workspace_title, title, surface_ref, system, user}], deferred, resume_cmd}. Each pending item is one surface's unread digest already framed as a prompt — `system` is the worklog-summary instruction, `user` is the captured output. (2) For each pending item dispatch a subagent (Task tool) using the Haiku model whose prompt is that item's `system` text followed by its `user` text, instructing it to return ONLY the worklog bullets and nothing else; dispatch all of a pass's items in parallel in one message. Do NOT read the raw journal/digest lines into your own context — the subagents do the reading. (3) Collect each subagent's bullets and pipe one JSON document {\"summaries\": [{\"digest_file\": <the item's digest_file>, \"bullets\": <that subagent's output>}]} over stdin to python3 <skill-dir>/summarize.py record-summaries. It appends the bullets to $OBSIDIAN/worklog/<date>.md under an hourly '## <HH:MM> — <workspace_title>' heading and marks ONLY those digest files summarized in the manifest, and ONLY after a successful append — so a subagent that failed (just omit it from summaries) or an append error leaves that digest pending for the next pass, and a replayed record-summaries never double-appends (the manifest is the exactly-once guard across the author gap). If collect's result has a non-empty `deferred` array, MORE THAN one day of un-summarized backlog exists and only days within the 1-day cap were collected; surface those dates to the user and only after they approve run the reported `resume_cmd` (python3 <skill-dir>/summarize.py collect --catch-up …). Never auto-run the >1-day catch-up without the user's go-ahead. (The summarize.py run path — POSTing digests to a configured OpenAI-compatible LLM — is the alternative backend the durable launchd job uses; see summarizer_component. It stays available but is not what the attached consumer runs.)"

block process_failure_finding(report_only, handler)
    description: "Act on a single failure finding by its tier: report-only, a safe auto-fix (send-enter or a learned resolution like resend), or a non-blocking hand-off of risky cases to the designated handler agent via the p2p skill."

    flow:
        if report_only
            "Report the finding to the user verbatim — surface_ref, title, workspace, signature, label, redacted evidence, and the binary's suggested remediation — and take no action at all, not even a safe auto-fix or a handler hand-off."
        elif "the finding's signature is unsent_p2p (tier safe)"
            "Run: python3 <skill-dir>/watchdog.py send-enter --surface <surface_ref> --workspace <workspace_ref> using the finding's refs. The binary re-reads the pane, confirms an unsent frame is still in the composer, presses Enter, and re-reads to confirm it cleared — so it is self-verifying and a no-op if the composer is already empty. Surface the result's note to the user; if cleared is false, the frame survived the Enter, so point the user at the surface and do not retry blindly."
        elif "the finding carries a known_resolution (the binary graduated it to tier safe from a learned resolution)"
            "Auto-apply the learned action. When known_resolution is resend, run: python3 <skill-dir>/watchdog.py resend --surface <surface_ref> --workspace <workspace_ref>. The binary recalls the last input (Up) and resubmits it (Enter), then re-reads to confirm the agent resumed — self-verifying and safe. Surface the result's note and resumed flag to the user; if resumed is false, point them at the surface and do not retry blindly."
        elif "no handler agent is configured for this run (handler is none), so this risky finding has nobody to route to"
            "This finding is risky and there is no handler to route to, so do not act autonomously: surface its evidence and the binary's suggested remediation to the user and let them decide."
        else
            "This finding is risky (an api_error whose label has no learned resolution, an exited agent, or anything ambiguous), and the loop must not block. Hand it off to the designated handler agent {handler} through the p2p skill — load the p2p skill and send via it, never the p2p binary directly. Compose a payload carrying the finding's surface_ref, workspace_ref, signature, label, redacted evidence, and the binary's suggested remediation, plus the exact follow-up command for the handler to run once a fix is confirmed so future recurrences auto-graduate to safe: python3 <skill-dir>/watchdog.py record-resolution --label <the finding's label> --action <the action that cleared it, e.g. resend>. Poke the healthy handler, not the failing pane — a stalled pane cannot read a message; the handler investigates and typically clears a stall with the resend pattern (Up then Enter). If the p2p skill reports the handler is unknown or offline (a peer_unknown handoff), do not spawn one — that is tfork's job and out of scope here: leave the finding in the inbox and take no further action, because having no consumer to act right now is acceptable. Never pause the loop waiting on the user for a risky finding."

const boundary_returns_handoffs = "Never shell out to the p2p or tfork binaries. Pressing Enter on a composer via watchdog.py send-enter is a raw cmux action (the message text is already pasted — only the final Enter is missing), so it is allowed. But re-composing a p2p message — including the risky-finding hand-off to the handler agent — or forking a replacement agent belongs to those skills: surface the need and invoke the p2p or tfork skill, do not reimplement them here."

const auto_safe_handoff_risky = "Auto-apply remediation only for tier-safe findings: the send-enter fix for an unsent_p2p finding, and — for a finding the binary graduated to safe via a learned resolution (it carries a known_resolution) — the stored action, e.g. resend. Every risky finding (an api_error whose label has no learned resolution, an exited agent, anything ambiguous) is handed to the designated handler agent via the p2p skill and the loop moves on — it never blocks on the user; when no handler is configured the finding is surfaced to the user instead, and when report_only is set no action is taken at all. The periodic worklog summary is separate and benign — it only digests captured output and appends bullets to the vault — and runs without pausing. But it has exactly one owner at a time (single_summary_owner): when the durable launchd summarizer is active it owns summarization, so the consumer treats summarize_due ticks as no-ops and skips the attach drain; only when launchd is NOT active does the consumer run the agent-authored pass itself (summarize.py collect, dispatch a summary subagent per surface, then summarize.py record-summaries) on each tick / on attach. Either way a >1-day backlog is flagged via `deferred` rather than churned, and surfaced to the user before the older catch-up runs."

const single_summary_owner = "Summarization has exactly ONE active owner, because every summary pass — the launchd HTTP `run` AND the consumer's agent-authored `collect` — runs watchdog.py digest, which advances a shared per-surface read-cursor; if two summarizers run, whoever digests first consumes the lines and the other gets an empty, partial result, splitting each hour's output. (collect and run both take an advisory flock around the digest+manifest step so an accidental overlap is rejected with skipped:'already_running' rather than racing; and record-summaries is idempotent — it marks/appends only the digests it authored and skips already-summarized ones — so the summary_state.json manifest is the real exactly-once guard across the collect->subagents->record gap the flock cannot span. The owner rule still avoids needless churn.) The durable launchd summarizer is the default owner when present: a consumer treats it as the owner when `launchctl print gui/<uid>/com.cmux-watchdog.summarizer` exits 0 (loaded). Once it is installed and loaded, the interactive consumer must NOT run summarize.py collect / digest itself — it treats summarize_due ticks as no-ops and skips the attach-time drain, keeping only capture (the producer), failure detection, and safe remediation. The consumer runs the agent-authored summary pass itself ONLY when the launchd job is absent or inactive (the intended default here — summarization is deliberately in-agent, no key needed; also covers install-failed). An explicit user 'summarize now' may still run one pass on demand. Never have both the launchd job and the consumer digesting concurrently."

const local_only = "watchdog.py makes no network calls and uses no provider SDKs or API keys: it only shells out to cmux and reads or writes local journal, inbox, and digest files — it never summarizes. Summarization lives entirely in the separate sibling summarize.py, which reads the digests watchdog.py produced. It has two backends: the default attached-consumer path is agent-authored — summarize.py collect hands the digests back as prompts and the consumer's own subagents write the bullets, so no network call or API key is involved — while the autonomous launchd path (summarize.py run) calls a generic OpenAI-compatible chat-completions API (DeepSeek-V4 by default; configurable via LLM_API_BASE / LLM_MODEL / LLM_API_KEY in env or ~/.cmux-watchdog/summarizer.env). Either way bullets are appended directly to $OBSIDIAN/worklog/<date>.md (plain markdown append, robust under launchd's minimal env). This split keeps watchdog.py deterministic and network-free while letting summarization run either from an attached agent or with no agent attached."

const focus_changes = "Switching the visible workspace or yanking pane focus while watching. The watchdog only reads screens and sends Enter to the exact target surface; it never calls select-workspace, focus-pane, or focus-panel, because the user may be looking at a different workspace."

const binary_contract = """watchdog.py is deterministic and exposes seven subcommands, each emitting JSON:
- snapshot [--workspace <ref|title|all>] [--lines N] [--max-scrollback-bytes N]: one-shot, READ-ONLY dashboard capture. Default scope is ALL workspaces (cross-workspace), unlike scan/watch which default to the caller's. Reads `tree --all` + `top --all` + `version`, classifies every surface (type via cmux tag or scrollback heuristic; state via cmux tag or the v1.2 scrollback ladder, emitting a state_classifier failure on a tag↔scrollback disagreement), redacts each read screen, and prints a versioned capture envelope: {capture_schema_version, captured_at, host, cmux_version, scope, workspaces:[{ref,title,window_ref,surfaces:[{ref,pane_ref,kind(terminal|browser),title,tty,cwd,cpu_pct,mem_bytes,is_agent}]}], agents:[{surface_ref,workspace_ref,type,type_source,type_confidence,state,state_source,pid}], captures:[{surface_ref,redacted_scrollback,screen_hash,redactions_applied}], failures:[...]}. `--lines` is the scrollback depth read per surface (default 150); `--max-scrollback-bytes` caps each redacted capture (default 4096). It touches NO journal / digest / cursor / inbox state and needs no producer — share the pure parse/classify/redact helpers with scan/watch but never run it as a watch tick. This is the cross-skill contract consumed by cmux-observability; bump capture_schema_version on a breaking change and consumers reject unsupported majors.
- scan [--workspace <ref|title|all>]: one-shot. Prints {ok, run_id, scope, candidates: [...]}. Each candidate carries surface_ref, workspace_ref, workspace_title, title, signature, label (the granular sub-type), tier (safe | risky), remediation, detail, known_resolution (set when a learned resolution graduated it), and a redacted evidence snippet. Excludes the watchdog's own controlling pane. Does not journal. Used both for a one-shot {once} check and as the consumer's attach-time catch-up.
- watch [--workspace <...>] [--interval <seconds>] [--summary-interval <seconds>]: loops scan, printing NDJSON — a {event: watching, ...} banner, one {event: finding, ...} line per newly detected failure, and one {event: summarize_due, ...} line every summary-interval seconds (0 disables). On every tick it also journals newly-settled pane output to per-surface append-only logs under ~/.cmux-watchdog/journal/<date>/. Runs detached as the single producer, its NDJSON appended to the inbox file the consumer tails. Re-emits a finding only after it clears and recurs. Both watch and scan exclude the watchdog's own controlling pane (resolved from CMUX_SURFACE_ID, UUID mapped to surface:N via `cmux identify`) from detection and journaling, so the watcher never flags itself; nothing is skipped when CMUX_SURFACE_ID is unset.
- digest [--workspace <...>] [--date <YYYY-MM-DD>]: writes each in-scope surface's unread journal lines (read-cursor to end of file) to a digest_file under ~/.cmux-watchdog/digests/<date>/, advances that surface's cursor, and prints {ok, date, scope, surfaces: [{surface_ref, workspace_title, title, digest_file, unread_line_count, from_cursor, to_cursor}]}. The cursor guarantees each captured line is digested exactly once.
- send-enter --surface <ref> --workspace <ref>: the safe remediation for unsent_p2p. Confirms an unsent frame is present, presses Enter, re-reads, and reports {ok, action, cleared, note}. Idempotent.
- resend --surface <ref> --workspace <ref>: recall the last input (send-key Up) and resubmit it (send-key Enter), then re-read to confirm the agent resumed (an active marker appeared, or the screen changed). Prints {ok, action, resumed, surface_ref, note}. Self-verifying and safe — the proven fix for an api_error that stalled an agent.
- record-resolution --label <granular-label> --action <action>: persist the action that resolved a finding, keyed by the granular api-error label (server_5xx / overloaded / rate_limit / api_error / connection / timeout), to <state-root>/resolutions.json (respects CMUX_WATCHDOG_HOME). On a later scan or watch tick, a finding whose label has a stored resolution is graduated risky -> safe with remediation set to that action plus a known_resolution annotation; labels with no stored resolution stay risky. Prints {ok, label, action}. The handler agent runs this after a confirmed fix.
Default scope is the caller's workspace (CMUX_WORKSPACE_ID); pass --workspace to widen or retarget. Journal and evidence text is redacted before it touches disk; raw secrets never reach this agent."""

const summarizer_component = """summarize.py is the summarizer — a sibling script in the same skill dir, deliberately separate from watchdog.py so the binary stays network-free and model-free. It offers TWO interchangeable summary backends over the same per-surface digest cursor + summary_state.json manifest (which together make every captured line summarized exactly once): an agent-authored path (collect + record-summaries) used by an attached consumer, and an HTTP path (run) used by the durable launchd job. Exactly one is the active owner at a time (single_summary_owner). Subcommands:
- collect [--workspace <...>] [--max-days N] [--catch-up]: the agent-authored path's read step. Under an advisory lock it shells out to watchdog.py digest, registers the new digest files in the manifest, and prints {ok, pending: [{digest_file, date, workspace_title, title, surface_ref, system, user}], deferred, resume_cmd} — NO LLM call. Each pending item frames one surface's unread digest as a prompt (`system` = the worklog-summary instruction, identical to the HTTP payload's; `user` = the captured output). The attached consumer dispatches a subagent per item to author the bullets, then records them. Same bounded autonomy as run: only days within --max-days (default 1) are returned; older backlog is in `deferred` with a `resume_cmd`. --catch-up lifts the cap. Needs OBSIDIAN but no LLM_API_KEY.
- record-summaries (reads {\"summaries\": [{digest_file, bullets}]} on stdin): the agent-authored path's write step. Appends each authored bullets block to $OBSIDIAN/worklog/<date>.md under '## <HH:MM> — <workspace_title>' and marks ONLY those digests summarized in the manifest, ONLY after a successful append. Idempotent: unknown digest_files, already-summarized ones, and blank bullets are skipped, so a replay or a stray concurrent run never double-appends. An append failure for a date marks nothing for that date (it retries). Needs OBSIDIAN only.
- run [--workspace <...>] [--max-days N] [--catch-up] [--date YYYY-MM-DD]: the HTTP path — one self-contained summary pass. Shells out to watchdog.py digest, sends each surface's unread digest to the configured OpenAI-compatible chat-completions endpoint (POST <LLM_API_BASE>/chat/completions, model <LLM_MODEL>; default DeepSeek-V4 'deepseek-v4-flash'), and appends the returned bullets like record-summaries does. Same catch-up + 1-day cap + `deferred`/`resume_cmd` semantics. --catch-up lifts the cap; --date forces a single day. This is what the launchd job runs; it needs LLM_API_KEY.
- install [--interval N] [--workspace <...>] [--label L] [--load] [--run-at-load]: render a macOS launchd LaunchAgent plist at ~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.cmux-watchdog.summarizer.plist that runs `summarize.py run` every N seconds, baking in absolute python + script paths and the workspace scope; with --load it launchctl-bootstraps the job immediately. This is the durable autonomous trigger — it survives reboot / logout / agent crash, so hourly summaries land with NO agent attached. Prints the load_cmd and stop_cmd (launchctl bootout) to manage it.
Config resolves from process env first, then from KEY=VALUE files in precedence order (earlier wins): ~/.cmux-watchdog/summarizer.env (skill override) then ~/genesis/.env (shared secrets). Keys: LLM_API_KEY (or DEEPSEEK_API_KEY) — needed only for the HTTP run/launchd path, not the agent-authored path — plus LLM_API_BASE, LLM_MODEL, OBSIDIAN (~ and $VARS in OBSIDIAN are expanded). One of these files is REQUIRED for the launchd job, which does not inherit your interactive shell environment. The HTTP call is plain OpenAI-compatible over stdlib (no SDK dependency), so any compatible provider works by changing LLM_API_BASE / LLM_MODEL.
Robustness: a run is crash/failure-safe. digest advances the journal cursor when it writes a digest FILE, so the durable unit is the digest file: a per-file summary-state manifest marks a file summarized ONLY after its bullets are appended, so a failed LLM call / append / non-200 retries on the next run instead of being silently lost (per-file LLM errors are caught and reported in `failed`; an append failure returns ok:false with nothing committed). An advisory flock serialises runs — a second concurrent run (launchd vs a manual run vs a consumer) returns {ok:true, skipped:'already_running'} rather than racing the cursor. `install --load` returns ok:false / nonzero if `launchctl bootstrap` fails (it never claims a job is loaded when it isn't); it also prints a status_cmd (`launchctl print gui/<uid>/<label>`, which exits 0 iff the job is loaded) so a consumer can deterministically tell loaded vs plist-only vs absent. A workspace UUID is rejected for `install` (the launchd job has no caller context to resolve it) — pass a workspace:N ref, a title, or 'all'."""

const failure_signatures = """The binary detects two failure signatures from a pane's screen:
- unsent_p2p (tier safe): a p2p [from: <peer>] frame is sitting in the input composer with no agent output or activity below it — the message was pasted but the final Enter never registered. Remediation: send-enter.
- api_error (tier risky): a known API or transport error (overloaded / 5xx / rate limit / connection / timeout) appears in recent output, which usually stalls the agent. Remediation: hand off to the designated handler agent via the p2p skill — the handler investigates and typically clears a stall with the resend pattern (Up then Enter), then records the resolution. But once a resolution has been recorded for the error's granular label, a recurrence graduates to tier safe and the stored action (e.g. resend) is auto-applied without a hand-off."""

const journal_model = """Capture is best-effort; digestion is exact. The watch loop diffs each pane snapshot against the last, strips volatile composer / footer / spinner chrome, and appends only newly-settled output lines (overlap-anchored) to the surface's daily journal. A burst larger than the read window between ticks can drop lines — those are flagged with a gap marker rather than silently lost. But every line that reaches the journal is summarized by summarize.py exactly once, because digest advances a per-surface read-cursor: no captured line is skipped or double-counted."""

const inbox_model = """Capture and consumption are decoupled. A single always-on producer — `watchdog.py watch` launched detached with its stdout appended to ~/.cmux-watchdog/inbox/findings.ndjson — captures, detects, and journals every tick, whether or not any agent is attached. It re-emits a finding only after it clears and recurs, and that dedup state lives in the one producer process, so there must be exactly one (a second would double-journal). The consumer is this skill running inside an agent; it may or may not be present. On attach it drains the backlog — a one-shot scan for currently-active failures the producer will not re-emit, plus a worklog-summary pass over unread journal lines — then tails the inbox and reacts to each event live. When no consumer is attached, findings simply accumulate in the inbox unhandled, which is acceptable: the next consumer to attach catches up via the attach-time scan."""
